# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: blockchain-scalability
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:blockchain-scalability/bitcoin-scalability] Several Layer 2 solutions have been implemented as a result.
[src:blockchain-scalability/bitcoin-scalability] The Lightning Network allows near-instant, low-fee payments that settle on the Bitcoin base layer.
[src:blockchain-scalability/bitcoin-scalability] The Liquid Network is a sidechain built on top of Bitcoin which processes blocks every minute instead of every 10 minutes.
[src:blockchain-scalability/bitcoin-scalability] The block size limit, in concert with the proof-of-work difficulty adjustment settings of bitcoin's consensus protocol, constitutes a bottleneck in bitcoin's transaction processing capacity.
[src:blockchain-scalability/bitcoin-scalability] This can result in increasing transaction fees and delayed processing of transactions that cannot be fit into a block.
[src:blockchain-scalability/bitcoin-scalability] Various proposals have come forth on how to scale bitcoin, and a contentious debate has resulted.
[src:blockchain-scalability/bitcoin-scalability] Technical optimizations may decrease the amount of computing resources required to receive, process and record bitcoin transactions, allowing increased throughput without placing extra demand on the bitcoin network.
[src:blockchain-scalability/bitcoin-scalability] These modifications can be to either the network, in which case a fork is required, or to individual node software (such as Bitcoin Core).
[src:blockchain-scalability/bitcoin-scalability] The Lightning Network (LN) is a protocol that aims to improve bitcoin's scalability and speed without sacrificing trustless operation.
[src:blockchain-scalability/bitcoin-scalability] The Lightning Network requires putting a funding transaction on the blockchain to open a payment channel.
[src:blockchain-scalability/bitcoin-scalability] Once a channel is opened, connected participants are able to make rapid payments within the channel or may route payments by "hopping" between channels at intermediate nodes for little to no fee.
[src:blockchain-scalability/bitcoin-scalability] In January 2018 Blockstream launched a payment processing system for web retailers called "Lightning Charge", noted that lightning was live on mainnet with 200 nodes operating as of 27 January 2018 and advised it should still be considered "in testing".
[src:blockchain-scalability/bitcoin-scalability] The Liquid Network is a sidechain that Blockstream developed which is built on top of Bitcoin.
[src:blockchain-scalability/bitcoin-scalability] It processes blocks every minute instead of every 10 minutes.
[src:blockchain-scalability/bitcoin-scalability] On 15 March 2018, Lightning Labs released the beta version of its lnd Lightning Network implementation for bitcoin mainnet, and on 28 March 2018, ACINQ released a mainnet beta of its eclair implementation and desktop application.
[src:blockchain-scalability/bitcoin-scalability] In January 2019 the online retailer Bitrefill announced that it receives more payments in Bitcoin via the lightning network than any other cryptocurrency they accept.
[src:blockchain-scalability/bitcoin-scalability] In June 2021, the Legislative Assembly of El Salvador voted legislation to make Bitcoin legal tender in El Salvador.
[src:blockchain-scalability/bitcoin-scalability] The decision was based on the success of the Bitcoin Beach ecosystem in El Zonte that used a LN based wallet.
[src:blockchain-scalability/bitcoin-scalability] The government will be introducing a wallet utilising the Lightning Network protocol while giving the freedom for citizens to use other Bitcoin Lightning wallets.
[src:blockchain-scalability/bitcoin-scalability] In 2025, El Salvador's bitcoin project was discontinued as a whole.
[src:blockchain-scalability/bitcoin-scalability] Bitcoin has a block time of 10 minutes and a block size of 1 MB.
[src:blockchain-scalability/bitcoin-scalability] Various increases to this limit, and proposals to remove it completely, have been proposed over bitcoin's history.
[src:blockchain-scalability/bitcoin-scalability] Implementing any of these proposals involves a fork.
[src:blockchain-scalability/bitcoin-scalability] Litecoin produces blocks four times faster than Bitcoin which leads to a 4x improvement in throughput.
[src:blockchain-scalability/bitcoin-scalability] Dogecoin has even more throughput with a block time of 1 minute.
[src:blockchain-scalability/bitcoin-scalability] Bitcoin Cash has a block size of 32 MB and hence 32x more throughput than Bitcoin.
[src:blockchain-scalability/bitcoin-scalability] Bitcoin SV removed the block size limit altogether.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] A **blockchain** is a distributed ledger with growing lists of records (*blocks*) that are securely linked together via cryptographic hashes.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] Each block contains a cryptographic hash of the previous block, a timestamp, and transaction data (generally represented as a Merkle tree, where data nodes are represented by leaves).
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] Since each block contains information about the previous block, they effectively form a *chain* (*viz.* linked list data structure), with each additional block linking to the ones before it.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] Consequently, blockchain transactions are resistant to alteration because, once recorded, the data in any given block cannot be changed retroactively without altering all subsequent blocks and obtaining network consensus to accept these changes.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] Blockchains are typically managed by a peer-to-peer (P2P) computer network for use as a public distributed ledger, where nodes collectively adhere to a consensus algorithm protocol to add and validate new transaction blocks.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] Although blockchain records are not unalterable, since blockchain forks are possible, blockchains may be considered secure by design and exemplify a distributed computing system with high Byzantine fault tolerance.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] A blockchain was created by a person (or group of people) using the name (or pseudonym) Satoshi Nakamoto in 2008 to serve as the public distributed ledger for bitcoin cryptocurrency transactions, based on previous work by Stuart Haber, W.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] The implementation of the blockchain within bitcoin made it the first digital currency to solve the double-spending problem without the need for a trusted authority or central server.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] The bitcoin design has inspired other applications and blockchains that are readable by the public and are widely used by cryptocurrencies.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] The blockchain may be considered a type of payment rail.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] Private blockchains have been proposed for business use.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] *Computerworld* called the marketing of such privatized blockchains without a proper security model "snake oil"; however, others have argued that permissioned blockchains, if carefully designed, may be more decentralized and therefore more secure in practice than permissionless ones.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] Cryptographer David Chaum first proposed a blockchain-like protocol in his 1982 dissertation "Computer Systems Established, Maintained, and Trusted by Mutually Suspicious Groups".
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] Further work on a cryptographically secured chain of blocks was described in 1991 by Stuart Haber and W.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] They wanted to implement a system wherein document timestamps could not be tampered with.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] In 1992, Haber, Stornetta, and Dave Bayer incorporated Merkle trees into the design, which improved its efficiency by allowing several document certificates to be collected into one block.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] Under their company Surety, their document certificate hashes have been published in *The New York Times* every week since 1995.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] The first decentralized blockchain was conceptualized by a person (or group of people) known as Satoshi Nakamoto in 2008.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] Nakamoto improved the design in an important way using a Hashcash-like method to timestamp blocks without requiring them to be signed by a trusted party and introducing a difficulty parameter to stabilize the rate at which blocks are added to the chain.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] The design was implemented the following year by Nakamoto as a core component of the cryptocurrency bitcoin, where it serves as the public ledger for all transactions on the network.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] In August 2014, the bitcoin blockchain file size, containing records of all transactions that have occurred on the network, reached 20 GB (gigabytes).
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] By 2024, the bitcoin blockchain exceeded 600 GB.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] The words *block* and *chain* were used separately in Satoshi Nakamoto's original paper, but were eventually popularized as a single word, *blockchain*, by 2016.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] According to Accenture, an application of the diffusion of innovations theory suggests that blockchains attained a 13.5% adoption rate within financial services in 2016, therefore reaching the early adopters' phase.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] Industry trade groups joined to create the Global Blockchain Forum in 2016, an initiative of the Chamber of Digital Commerce.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] In May 2018, Gartner found that only 1% of CIOs indicated any kind of blockchain adoption within their organisations, and only 8% of CIOs were in the short-term "planning or [looking at] active experimentation with blockchain".
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] For the year 2019 Gartner reported 5% of CIOs believed blockchain technology was a 'game-changer' for their business.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] A blockchain is a decentralized, distributed, and often public, digital ledger consisting of records called *blocks* that are used to record transactions across many computers so that any involved block cannot be altered retroactively, without the alteration of all subsequent blocks.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] This allows the participants to verify and audit transactions independently and relatively inexpensively.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] A blockchain database is managed autonomously using a peer-to-peer network and a distributed timestamping server.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] They are authenticated by mass collaboration powered by collective self-interests.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] Such a design facilitates robust workflow where participants' uncertainty regarding data security is marginal.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] The use of a blockchain removes the characteristic of infinite reproducibility from a digital asset.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] It confirms that each unit of value was transferred only once, solving the long-standing problem of double-spending.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] A blockchain has been described as a *value-exchange protocol*.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] Blocks hold batches of valid transactions that are hashed and encoded into a Merkle tree.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] Each block includes the cryptographic hash of the prior block in the blockchain, linking the two.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] This iterative process confirms the integrity of the previous block, all the way back to the initial block, which is known as the *genesis block* (Block 0).
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] To assure the integrity of a block and the data contained in it, the block is usually digitally signed.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] Sometimes separate blocks can be produced concurrently, creating a temporary fork.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] In addition to a secure hash-based history, any blockchain has a specified algorithm for scoring different versions of the history so that one with a higher score can be selected over others.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] Blocks not selected for inclusion in the chain are called orphan blocks.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] Peers supporting the database have different versions of the history from time to time.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] They keep only the highest-scoring version of the database known to them.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] Whenever a peer receives a higher-scoring version (usually the old version with a single new block added) they extend or overwrite their own database and retransmit the improvement to their peers.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] There is never an absolute guarantee that any particular entry will remain in the best version of history forever.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] Blockchains are typically built to add the score of new blocks onto old blocks and are given incentives to extend with new blocks rather than overwrite old blocks.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] Therefore, the probability of an entry becoming superseded decreases exponentially as more blocks are built on top of it, eventually becoming very low.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] For example, bitcoin uses a proof-of-work system, where the chain with the most cumulative proof-of-work is considered the valid one by the network.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] There are a number of methods that can be used to demonstrate a sufficient level of computation.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] Within a blockchain the computation is carried out redundantly rather than in the traditional segregated and parallel manner.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] The *block time* is the average time it takes for the network to generate one extra block in the blockchain.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] By the time of block completion, the included data becomes verifiable.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] In cryptocurrency, this is practically when the transaction takes place, so a shorter block time means faster transactions.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] Since 2022, the block time for Ethereum is set to exactly 12 seconds, while for bitcoin it is on average 10 minutes.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] A *hard fork* is a change to the blockchain protocol that is not backward compatible and requires all users to upgrade their software in order to continue participating in the network.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] In a hard fork, the network splits into two separate versions: one that follows the new rules and one that follows the old rules.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] For example, Ethereum was hard forked in 2016 to "make whole" the investors in The DAO, which had been hacked by exploiting a vulnerability in its code.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] In this case, the fork resulted in a split creating Ethereum and Ethereum Classic chains.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] In 2014, the Nxt community was asked to consider a hard fork that would have led to a rollback of the blockchain records to mitigate the effects of a theft of 50 million NXT from a major cryptocurrency exchange.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] The hard fork proposal was rejected, and some of the funds were recovered after negotiations and ransom payment.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] Alternatively, to prevent a permanent split, a majority of nodes using the new software may return to the old rules, as was the case with Bitcoin split on 12 March 2013.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] A more recent hard-fork example is of Bitcoin in 2017, which resulted in a split creating Bitcoin Cash.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] The network split was mainly due to a disagreement in how to increase the transactions per second to accommodate for demand.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] By storing data across its peer-to-peer network, the blockchain eliminates some risks that come with data being held centrally.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] The decentralized blockchain may use ad hoc message passing and distributed networking.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] In a so-called "51% attack" a central entity gains control of more than half of a network and can then manipulate that specific blockchain record at will, allowing double-spending.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] Blockchain security methods include the use of public-key cryptography.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] A *public key* (a long, random-looking string of numbers) is an address on the blockchain.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] Value tokens sent across the network are recorded as belonging to that address.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] A *private key* is like a password that gives its owner access to their digital assets or the means to otherwise interact with the various capabilities that blockchains now support.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] Data stored on the blockchain is generally considered incorruptible.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] Every node in a decentralized system has a copy of the blockchain.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] Data quality is maintained by massive database replication and computational trust.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] No centralized "official" copy exists and no user is "trusted" more than any other.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] Transactions are broadcast to the network using the software.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] Messages are delivered on a best-effort basis.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] Early blockchains rely on energy-intensive mining nodes to validate transactions, add them to the block they are building, and then broadcast the completed block to other nodes.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] Blockchains use various time-stamping schemes, such as proof-of-work, to serialize changes.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] Later consensus methods include proof of stake.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] The growth of a decentralized blockchain is accompanied by the risk of centralization because the computer resources required to process larger amounts of data become more expensive.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] Finality is the level of confidence that the well-formed block recently appended to the blockchain will not be revoked in the future (is "finalized") and thus can be trusted.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] Byzantine fault tolerance-based proof-of-stake protocols purport to provide so called "absolute finality": a randomly chosen validator proposes a block, the rest of validators vote on it, and, if a supermajority decision approves it, the block is irreversibly committed into the blockchain.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] A modification of this method, an "economic finality", is used in practical protocols, like the Casper protocol used in Ethereum: validators which sign two different blocks at the same position in the blockchain are subject to "slashing", where their leveraged stake is forfeited.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] Open blockchains are more user-friendly than some traditional ownership records, which, while open to the public, still require physical access to view.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] Because all early blockchains were permissionless, controversy has arisen over the blockchain definition.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] An issue in this ongoing debate is whether a private system with verifiers tasked and authorized (permissioned) by a central authority should be considered a blockchain.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] Proponents of permissioned or private chains argue that the term "blockchain" may be applied to any **data structure** that batches data into time-stamped blocks.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] These blockchains serve as a distributed version of multiversion concurrency control (MVCC) in databases.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] Just as MVCC prevents two transactions from concurrently modifying a single object in a database, blockchains prevent two transactions from spending the same single output in a blockchain.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] Opponents say that permissioned systems resemble traditional corporate databases, not supporting decentralized data verification, and that such systems are not hardened against operator tampering and revision.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] An advantage to an open, permissionless, or public, blockchain network is that guarding against bad actors is not required and no access control is needed.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] This means that applications can be added to the network without the approval or trust of others, using the blockchain as a transport layer.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] Bitcoin and other cryptocurrencies currently secure their blockchain by requiring new entries to include proof of work.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] To prolong the blockchain, bitcoin uses Hashcash puzzles.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] While Hashcash was designed in 1997 by Adam Back, the original idea was first proposed by Cynthia Dwork and Moni Naor and Eli Ponyatovski in their 1992 paper "Pricing via Processing or Combatting Junk Mail".
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] In 2016, venture capital investment for blockchain-related projects was weakening in the US but increasing in China.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] Bitcoin and many other cryptocurrencies use open (public) blockchains.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] As of April 2018, bitcoin has the highest market capitalization.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] Permissioned blockchains use an access control layer to govern who has access to the network.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] It has been argued that permissioned blockchains can guarantee a certain level of decentralization, if carefully designed, as opposed to permissionless blockchains, which are often centralized in practice.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] Nikolai Hampton argued in *Computerworld* that "There is also no need for a '51 percent' attack on a private blockchain, as the private blockchain (most likely) already controls 100 percent of all block creation resources.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] It's unlikely that any private blockchain will try to protect records using gigawatts of computing power — it's time-consuming and expensive." He also said, "Within a private blockchain there is also no 'race'; there's no incentive to use more power or discover blocks faster than competitors.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] The analysis of public blockchains has become increasingly important with the popularity of bitcoin, Ethereum, litecoin and other cryptocurrencies.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] A blockchain, if it is public, provides access to anyone to observe and analyse the chain data, given the know-how.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] The process of understanding and accessing the flow of crypto has been an issue for many cryptocurrencies, crypto exchanges and banks.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] The reason for this is accusations of blockchain-enabled cryptocurrencies enabling illicit dark market trading of drugs, weapons, money laundering, etc.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] A common belief has been that cryptocurrency is private and untraceable, thus leading many actors to use it for illegal purposes.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] This is changing now that specialised tech companies provide blockchain tracking services, making crypto exchanges, law-enforcement and banks more aware of what is happening with crypto funds and fiat-crypto exchanges.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] The development, some argue, has led criminals to prioritise the use of new cryptos such as Monero.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] In April 2016, Standards Australia submitted a proposal to the International Organization for Standardization to consider developing standards to support blockchain technology.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] This proposal resulted in the creation of ISO Technical Committee 307, Blockchain and Distributed Ledger Technologies.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] The technical committee has working groups relating to blockchain terminology, reference architecture, security and privacy, identity, smart contracts, governance and interoperability for blockchain and DLT, as well as standards specific to industry sectors and generic government requirements.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] Many other national standards bodies and open standards bodies are also working on blockchain standards.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] Although most of blockchain implementation are decentralized and distributed, Oracle launched a centralized blockchain table feature in Oracle 21c database.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] The Blockchain Table in Oracle 21c database is a centralized blockchain which provide immutable feature.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] Compared to decentralized blockchains, centralized blockchains normally can provide a higher throughput and lower latency of transactions than consensus-based distributed blockchains.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] Currently, there are at least four types of blockchain networks — public blockchains, private blockchains, consortium blockchains and hybrid blockchains.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] A public blockchain has no access restrictions.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] Anyone with an Internet connection can send transactions to it as well as become a validator (i.e., participate in the execution of a consensus protocol).
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] Usually, such networks offer economic incentives for those who secure them and utilize some type of a proof-of-stake or proof-of-work algorithm.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] Some of the largest, most known public blockchains are the bitcoin blockchain and the Ethereum blockchain.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] One cannot join it unless invited by the network administrators.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] Participant and validator access is restricted.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] To distinguish between open blockchains and other peer-to-peer decentralized database applications that are not open ad-hoc compute clusters, the terminology Distributed Ledger (DLT) is normally used for private blockchains.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] A hybrid blockchain has a combination of centralized and decentralized features.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] The exact workings of the chain can vary based on which portions of centralization and decentralization are used.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] A sidechain is a designation for a blockchain ledger that runs in parallel to a primary blockchain.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] A consortium blockchain is a type of blockchain that combines elements of both public and private blockchains.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] In a consortium blockchain, a group of organizations come together to create and operate the blockchain, rather than a single entity.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] The consortium members jointly manage the blockchain network and are responsible for validating transactions.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] Consortium blockchains are permissioned, meaning that only certain individuals or organizations are allowed to participate in the network.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] This allows for greater control over who can access the blockchain and helps to ensure that sensitive information is kept confidential.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] Consortium blockchains are commonly used in industries where multiple organizations need to collaborate on a common goal, such as supply chain management or financial services.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] One advantage of consortium blockchains is that they can be more efficient and scalable than public blockchains, as the number of nodes required to validate transactions is typically smaller.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] Additionally, consortium blockchains can provide greater security and reliability than private blockchains, as the consortium members work together to maintain the network.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] Some examples of consortium blockchains include Quorum and Hyperledger.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] The primary use of blockchains is as a distributed ledger for cryptocurrencies such as bitcoin; there were also a few other operational products that had matured from proof of concept by late 2016.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] As of 2016, some businesses have been testing the technology and conducting low-level implementation to gauge blockchain's effects on organizational efficiency in their back office.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] In 2019, it was estimated that around $2.9 billion were invested in blockchain technology, which represents an 89% increase from the year prior.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] A report from to PricewaterhouseCoopers (PwC) in 2021 said that blockchain technology had the potential to generate an annual business value of more than $3 trillion by 2030.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] PwC surveyed 600 business executives and determined that 84% have at least some exposure to utilizing blockchain technology.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] In 2019, the BBC World Service radio and podcast series *50 Things That Made the Modern Economy* identified blockchain as a technology that would have far-reaching consequences for economics and society.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] The economist and *Financial Times* journalist and broadcaster Tim Harford discussed why the underlying technology might have much wider applications and the challenges that needed to be overcome.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] His first broadcast was on 29 June 2019.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] Most cryptocurrencies are designed to gradually decrease the production of that currency, placing a cap on the total amount of that currency that will ever be in circulation.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] Compared with ordinary currencies held by financial institutions or kept as cash on hand, cryptocurrencies can be more difficult for seizure by law enforcement.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] The validity of each cryptocurrency's coins is provided by a blockchain.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] A blockchain is a continuously growing list of records, called blocks, which are linked and secured using cryptography.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] Each block typically contains a hash pointer as a link to a previous block, a timestamp and transaction data.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] By design, blockchains are inherently resistant to modification of the data.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] It is "an open, distributed ledger that can record transactions between two parties efficiently and in a verifiable and permanent way".
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] For use as a distributed ledger, a blockchain is typically managed by a peer-to-peer network collectively adhering to a protocol for validating new blocks.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] Once recorded, the data in any given block cannot be altered retroactively without the alteration of all subsequent blocks, which requires collusion of the network majority.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] Blockchains are secure by design and are an example of a distributed computing system with high Byzantine fault tolerance.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] Decentralized consensus has therefore been achieved with a blockchain.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] In the context of cryptocurrencies, the blockchain serves as a public ledger for all transactions.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] Cryptocurrencies use various timestamping schemes to "prove the validity of transactions added to the blockchain ledger without the need for a trusted third party".
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] The first cryptocurrency was Bitcoin, which was first released as open-source software in 2009.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] As cryptocurrencies have gained prominence, several countries have made advancements in their private and commercial law treatment to address legal uncertainties.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] In the United States, for example, the 2022 amendments to the Uniform Commercial Code (UCC) introduced Article 12, which establishes "controllable electronic records" (CERs) as a new category of personal property.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] This framework provides legal clarity for the ownership, transfer, and use of cryptocurrencies as CERs, with the concept of "control" serving as a functional equivalent to possession for digital assets.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] These reforms aim to align legal standards with market practices, reducing title disputes and supporting the integration of cryptocurrencies into commercial transactions.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] Blockchain-based smart contracts are contracts that can be partially or fully executed or enforced without human interaction.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] One of the main objectives of a smart contract is automated escrow.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] A key feature of smart contracts is that they do not need a trusted third party (such as a trustee) to act as an intermediary between contracting entities — the blockchain network executes the contract on its own.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] This may reduce friction between entities when transferring value and could subsequently open the door to a higher level of transaction automation.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] An IMF staff discussion from 2018 reported that smart contracts based on blockchain technology might reduce moral hazards and optimize the use of contracts in general, but "no viable smart contract systems have yet emerged." Due to the lack of widespread use, their legal status was unclear.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] According to *Reason* in 2016, many banks have expressed interest in implementing distributed ledgers for use in banking and are cooperating with companies creating private blockchains.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] According to a September 2016 IBM study, this implementation was occurring faster than expected.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] Blockchain technology has been proposed as a way to speed up back office settlement systems.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] In 2017, UBS opened a lab dedicated to researching how blockchain technology could be used in financial services.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] In 2017, the German bank Berenberg described blockchain as an "overhyped technology" that has had a large number of "proofs of concept", but still has major challenges, and very few success stories.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] Blockchain technology has allowed for new forms of fundraising such as initial coin offerings (ICOs) and security token offerings (STOs), also sometimes referred to as digital security offerings (DSOs).
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] STO/DSOs may be conducted privately or on public, regulated stock exchange and are used to tokenize assets such as company shares, intellectual property, real estate, and others.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] Blockchain technology, such as cryptocurrencies and non-fungible tokens (NFTs), has been used in video games for monetization.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] Many live-service games offer in-game customization options, such as character skins or other in-game items, which the players can earn and trade with other players using in-game currency.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] Blockchain games typically allow players to trade these in-game items for cryptocurrency, which can then be exchanged for money.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] The first known game to use blockchain technologies was *CryptoKitties*, launched in November 2017, where the player would purchase NFTs with Ethereum cryptocurrency, each NFT consisting of a virtual pet that the player could breed with others to create offspring with combined traits as new NFTs.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] The game made headlines in December 2017 when one virtual pet sold for more than US$100,000.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] *CryptoKitties* also illustrated scalability problems for games on Ethereum when it created significant congestion on the Ethereum network in early 2018 with approximately 30% of all Ethereum transactions being for the game.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] By the early 2020s, there had not been a breakout success in video games using blockchain, as these games tend to focus on using blockchain for speculation instead of more traditional forms of gameplay, which offers limited appeal to most players.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] Such games also represent a high risk to investors as their revenues can be difficult to predict.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] Several major publishers, including Ubisoft, Electronic Arts, and Take Two Interactive, have stated that blockchain and NFT-based games are under serious consideration for their companies in the future.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] Valve's prior history with gambling, specifically skin gambling, was speculated to be a factor in the decision to ban blockchain games.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] There have been several different efforts to employ blockchains in supply chain management.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] There are several different efforts to offer domain name services via the blockchain.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] These domain names can be controlled by the use of a private key, which purports to allow for uncensorable websites.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] This would also bypass a registrar's ability to suppress domains used for fraud, abuse, or illegal content.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] Namecoin is a cryptocurrency that supports the ".bit" top-level domain (TLD).
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] Namecoin was forked from bitcoin in 2011.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] The .bit TLD is not sanctioned by ICANN, instead requiring an alternative DNS root.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] As of 2015, .bit was used by 28 websites, out of 120,000 registered names.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] Namecoin was dropped by OpenNIC in 2019, due to malware and potential other legal issues.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] Other blockchain alternatives to ICANN include *The Handshake Network*, *EmerDNS*, and *Unstoppable Domains*.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] Specific TLDs include ".eth", ".luxe", and ".kred", which are associated with the Ethereum blockchain through the Ethereum Name Service (ENS).
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] The .kred TLD also acts as an alternative to conventional cryptocurrency wallet addresses as a convenience for transferring cryptocurrency.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] Blockchain technology can be used to create a permanent, public, transparent ledger system for compiling data on sales, tracking digital use and payments to content creators, such as wireless users or musicians.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] The Gartner 2019 CIO Survey reported 2% of higher education respondents had launched blockchain projects and another 18% were planning academic projects in the next 24 months.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] In 2017, IBM partnered with ASCAP and PRS for Music to adopt blockchain technology in music distribution.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] New distribution methods are available for the insurance industry such as peer-to-peer insurance, parametric insurance and microinsurance following the adoption of blockchain.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] The sharing economy and IoT are also set to benefit from blockchains because they involve many collaborating peers.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] The use of blockchain in libraries is being studied with a grant from the U.S.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] Institute of Museum and Library Services.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] Other blockchain designs include Hyperledger, a collaborative effort from the Linux Foundation to support blockchain-based distributed ledgers, with projects under this initiative including Hyperledger Burrow (by Monax) and Hyperledger Fabric (spearheaded by IBM).
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] Another is Quorum, a permissioned private blockchain by JPMorgan Chase with private storage, used for contract applications.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] Oracle introduced a blockchain table feature in its Oracle 21c database.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] Blockchain is also being used in peer-to-peer energy trading.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] Blockchain could be used in detecting counterfeits by associating unique identifiers to products, documents and shipments, and storing records associated with transactions that cannot be forged or altered.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] It is however argued that blockchain technology needs to be supplemented with technologies that provide a strong binding between physical objects and blockchain systems, as well as provisions for content creator verification *ala* KYC standards.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] The EUIPO established an Anti-Counterfeiting Blockathon Forum, with the objective of "defining, piloting and implementing" an anti-counterfeiting infrastructure at the European level.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] The Dutch Standardisation organisation NEN uses blockchain together with QR Codes to authenticate certificates.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] Beijing and Shanghai are among the cities designated by China to trial blockchain applications as January 30, 2022.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] In Chinese legal proceedings, blockchain technology was first accepted as a method for authenticating internet evidence by the Hangzhou Internet Court in 2019 and has since been accepted by other Chinese courts.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] With the increasing number of blockchain systems appearing, even only those that support cryptocurrencies, blockchain interoperability is becoming a topic of major importance.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] The objective is to support transferring assets from one blockchain system to another blockchain system.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] Wegner stated that "interoperability is the ability of two or more software components to cooperate despite differences in language, interface, and execution platform".
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] The objective of blockchain interoperability is therefore to support such cooperation among blockchain systems, despite those kinds of differences.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] There are already several blockchain interoperability solutions available.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] They can be classified into three categories: cryptocurrency interoperability approaches, blockchain engines, and blockchain connectors.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] Several individual IETF participants produced the draft of a blockchain interoperability architecture.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] Some cryptocurrencies use blockchain mining, namely the peer-to-peer computer computations by which transactions are validated and verified.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] In June 2018, the Bank for International Settlements criticized the use of public proof-of-work blockchains for their high energy consumption.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] Early concern over the high energy consumption was a factor in later blockchains such as Cardano (2017), Solana (2020) and Polkadot (2020) adopting the less energy-intensive proof-of-stake model.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] Researchers have estimated that bitcoin consumes 100,000 times as much energy as proof-of-stake networks.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] In 2021, a study by Cambridge University determined that bitcoin (at 121 terawatt-hours per year) used more electricity than Argentina (at 121TWh) and the Netherlands (109TWh).
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] According to Digiconomist, one bitcoin transaction required 708 kilowatt-hours of electrical energy, the amount an average U.S. household consumed in 24 days.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] Treasury secretary Janet Yellen called bitcoin "an extremely inefficient way to conduct transactions", saying "the amount of energy consumed in processing those transactions is staggering".
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] Nicholas Weaver, of the International Computer Science Institute at the University of California, Berkeley, examined blockchain's online security, and the energy efficiency of proof-of-work public blockchains, and in both cases found it grossly inadequate.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] The 31TWh-45TWh of electricity used for bitcoin in 2018 produced 17–23 million tonnes of CO2.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] By 2022, the University of Cambridge and Digiconomist estimated that the two largest proof-of-work blockchains, bitcoin and Ethereum, together used twice as much electricity in one year as the whole of Sweden, leading to the release of up to 120 million tonnes of CO2 each year.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] Some cryptocurrency developers are considering moving from the proof-of-work model to the proof-of-stake model.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] In Sept, 2022, Ethereum converted from proof-of-work to proof-of-stake.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] In October 2014, the MIT Bitcoin Club, with funding from MIT alumni, provided undergraduate students at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology access to $100 of bitcoin.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] The adoption rates, as studied by Catalini and Tucker (2016), revealed that when people who typically adopt technologies early are given delayed access, they tend to reject the technology.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] Many universities have founded departments focusing on crypto and blockchain, including MIT, in 2017.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] In the same year, Edinburgh became "one of the first big European universities to launch a blockchain course", according to the *Financial Times*.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] Motivations for adopting blockchain technology (an aspect of innovation adoption) have been investigated by researchers.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] For example, Janssen, et al. provided a framework for analysis, and Koens & Poll pointed out that adoption could be heavily driven by non-technical factors.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] Based on behavioral models, Li has discussed the differences between adoption at the individual level and organizational levels.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] Scholars in business and management have started studying the role of blockchains to support collaboration.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] It has been argued that blockchains can foster both cooperation (i.e., prevention of opportunistic behavior) and coordination (i.e., communication and information sharing).
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] Thanks to reliability, transparency, traceability of records, and information immutability, blockchains facilitate collaboration in a way that differs both from the traditional use of contracts and from relational norms.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] Contrary to contracts, blockchains do not directly rely on the legal system to enforce agreements.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] In addition, contrary to the use of relational norms, blockchains do not require a trust or direct connections between collaborators.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] The need for internal audits to provide effective oversight of organizational efficiency will require a change in the way that information is accessed in new formats.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] Blockchain adoption requires a framework to identify the risk of exposure associated with transactions using blockchain.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] The Institute of Internal Auditors has identified the need for internal auditors to address this transformational technology.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] New methods are required to develop audit plans that identify threats and risks.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] The Internal Audit Foundation study, *Blockchain and Internal Audit,* assesses these factors.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] The American Institute of Certified Public Accountants has outlined new roles for auditors as a result of blockchain.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] In blockchain technology, a **testnet** is an instance of a blockchain powered by the same or a newer version of the underlying software, to be used for testing and experimentation without risk to real funds or the main chain.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] Testnet coins are separate and distinct from the official *mainnet* coins, don't have value, and can be obtained freely from *faucets*.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] Testnets allow for the development of blockchain applications without the risk of losing funds.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] Using testnets, a bug was discovered in the Bitcoin Core software that gave miners the ability to take down essential parts of the Bitcoin infrastructure (nodes) by sending a 'bad' block to the blockchain.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] A **mainnet** (short for *main network*) is the fully operational version of a blockchain where real transactions occur, as opposed to a testnet.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] It is secured through consensus mechanisms like Proof of Work or Proof of Stake and supports smart contracts, token transfers, and decentralized applications.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] A *mainnet launch* marks the transition from a testnet to a live blockchain, involving security audits, network deployment, and token migration.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] In September 2015, the first peer-reviewed academic journal dedicated to cryptocurrency and blockchain technology research, *Ledger*, was announced.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] The inaugural issue was published in December 2016.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] The journal covers aspects of mathematics, computer science, engineering, law, economics and philosophy that relate to cryptocurrencies.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] The journal encourages authors to digitally sign a file hash of submitted papers, which are then timestamped into the bitcoin blockchain.
[src:blockchain-scalability/blockchain] Authors are also asked to include a personal bitcoin address on the first page of their papers for non-repudiation purposes.
[src:blockchain-scalability/data-availability] "Don't trust, verify" is a common maxim in Ethereum.
[src:blockchain-scalability/data-availability] The idea is that your node can independently verify that the information it receives is correct by executing all the transactions in the blocks they receive from peers to ensure that the changes proposed precisely match those computed independently by the node.
[src:blockchain-scalability/data-availability] This means nodes do not have to trust that the senders of the block are honest.
[src:blockchain-scalability/data-availability] This is not possible if data is missing.
[src:blockchain-scalability/data-availability] You should have a good understanding of blockchain fundamentals, especially consensus mechanisms.
[src:blockchain-scalability/data-availability] This page also assumes the reader is familiar with blocks, transactions, nodes, scaling solutions, and other relevant topics.
[src:blockchain-scalability/data-availability] The data availability problem is the need to prove to the whole network that the summarized form of some transaction data that is being added to the blockchain really represents a set of valid transactions, but doing so without requiring all nodes to download all data.
[src:blockchain-scalability/data-availability] The full transaction data is necessary for independently verifying blocks, but requiring all nodes to download all transaction data is a barrier to scaling.
[src:blockchain-scalability/data-availability] Solutions to the data availability problem aim to provide sufficient assurances that the full transaction data was made available for verification to network participants that do not download and store the data for themselves.
[src:blockchain-scalability/data-availability] Light nodes and Layer 2 rollups are important examples of network participants that require strong data availability assurances but cannot download and process transaction data for themselves.
[src:blockchain-scalability/data-availability] Avoiding downloading transaction data is what makes light nodes light and enables rollups to be effective scaling solutions.
[src:blockchain-scalability/data-availability] Data availability is also a critical concern for future "stateless" Ethereum clients that do not need to download and store state data in order to verify blocks.
[src:blockchain-scalability/data-availability] The stateless clients still need to be certain that the data is available *somewhere* and that it has been processed correctly.
[src:blockchain-scalability/data-availability] Data Availability Sampling (DAS) is a way for the network to check that data is available without putting too much strain on any individual node.
[src:blockchain-scalability/data-availability] Each node (including non-staking nodes) downloads some small, randomly selected subset of the total data.
[src:blockchain-scalability/data-availability] Successfully downloading the samples confirms with high confidence that all of the data is available.
[src:blockchain-scalability/data-availability] This relies upon data erasure coding, which expands a given dataset with redundant information (the way this is done is to fit a function known as a *polynomial* over the data and evaluating that polynomial at additional points).
[src:blockchain-scalability/data-availability] This allows the original data to be recovered from the redundant data when necessary.
[src:blockchain-scalability/data-availability] A consequence of this data creation is that if *any* of the original data is unavailable, *half* of the expanded data will be missing!
[src:blockchain-scalability/data-availability] The amount of data samples downloaded by each node can be tuned so that it is *extremely* likely that at least one of the data fragments sampled by each client will be missing *if* less than half the data is really available.
[src:blockchain-scalability/data-availability] DAS will be used to ensure rollup operators make their transaction data available after Full Danksharding has been implemented.
[src:blockchain-scalability/data-availability] Ethereum nodes will randomly sample the transaction data provided in blobs using the redundancy scheme explained above to ensure that all the data exists.
[src:blockchain-scalability/data-availability] The same technique could also be employed to ensure block producers are making all their data available to secure light clients.
[src:blockchain-scalability/data-availability] Similarly, under proposer-builder separation, only the block builder would be required to process an entire block - other validators would verify using data availability sampling.
[src:blockchain-scalability/data-availability] Data Availability Committees (DACs) are trusted parties that provide, or attest to, data availability.
[src:blockchain-scalability/data-availability] DACs can be used instead of, or in combination with (opens in a new tab) DAS.
[src:blockchain-scalability/data-availability] The security guarantees that come with committees depends on the specific set up.
[src:blockchain-scalability/data-availability] Ethereum uses randomly sampled subsets of validators to attest to data availability for light nodes, for example.
[src:blockchain-scalability/data-availability] The DAC is a trusted set of nodes that stores copies of data offline.
[src:blockchain-scalability/data-availability] The DAC is required to make the data available in the event of a dispute.
[src:blockchain-scalability/data-availability] Members of the DAC also publish onchain attestations to prove that the said data is indeed available.
[src:blockchain-scalability/data-availability] Some validiums replace DACs with a proof-of-stake (PoS) validator system.
[src:blockchain-scalability/data-availability] Here, anyone can become a validator and store data offchain.
[src:blockchain-scalability/data-availability] However, they must provide a “bond”, which is deposited in a smart contract.
[src:blockchain-scalability/data-availability] In the event of malicious behavior, such as the validator withholding data, the bond can be slashed.
[src:blockchain-scalability/data-availability] Proof-of-stake data availability committees are considerably more secure than regular DACs because they directly incentivize honest behavior.
[src:blockchain-scalability/data-availability] Light nodes need to validate the correctness of the block headers they receive without downloading the block data.
[src:blockchain-scalability/data-availability] The cost of this lightness is the inability to independently verify the block headers by re-executing transactions locally in the way full nodes do.
[src:blockchain-scalability/data-availability] Ethereum light nodes trust random sets of 512 validators that have been assigned to a *sync committee*.
[src:blockchain-scalability/data-availability] The sync committee acts as a DAC that signals to light clients that the data in the header is correct using a cryptographic signature.
[src:blockchain-scalability/data-availability] Every day, the sync committee refreshes.
[src:blockchain-scalability/data-availability] Each block header alerts light nodes as to which validators to expect to sign off the *next* block, so they can't be tricked into trusting a malicious group pretending to be the real sync-committee.
[src:blockchain-scalability/data-availability] However, what happens if an attacker somehow *does* manage to pass a malicious block header to light clients and convince them that it was signed off by an honest sync-committee?
[src:blockchain-scalability/data-availability] In that case, the attacker could include invalid transactions and the light client would blindly accept them, as they do not independently check all the state changes summarized in the block header.
[src:blockchain-scalability/data-availability] To protect against this, the light client could use fraud proofs.
[src:blockchain-scalability/data-availability] Light nodes could pick up those fraud-proofs and use them to discard bad block headers, ensuring they stay on the same honest chain as the full nodes.
[src:blockchain-scalability/data-availability] This relies on full nodes having access to full transaction data.
[src:blockchain-scalability/data-availability] An attacker who broadcasts a bad block header and also fails to make the transaction data available would be able to prevent full nodes from generating fraud proofs.
[src:blockchain-scalability/data-availability] The full nodes might be able to signal a warning about a bad block, but they couldn't back up their warning with proof, because the data wasn't made available to generate the proof from!
[src:blockchain-scalability/data-availability] The solution to this data availability problem is DAS.
[src:blockchain-scalability/data-availability] Light nodes download very small random chunks of the full state data and use the samples to verify that the full data set is available.
[src:blockchain-scalability/data-availability] The actual likelihood of incorrectly assuming full data availability after downloading N random chunks can be calculated (for 100 chunks the chance is 10^-30 (opens in a new tab), i.e., incredibly unlikely).
[src:blockchain-scalability/data-availability] Even in this scenario, attacks that withhold just a few bytes could feasibly go unnoticed by clients making random data requests.
[src:blockchain-scalability/data-availability] Erasure coding fixes this by reconstructing small missing pieces of data that can be used to check proposed state changes.
[src:blockchain-scalability/data-availability] A fraud proof could then be constructed using the reconstructed data, preventing light nodes from accepting bad headers.
[src:blockchain-scalability/data-availability] Layer 2 scaling solutions, such as , reduce transaction costs and increase Ethereum's throughput by processing transactions offchain.
[src:blockchain-scalability/data-availability] Rollup transactions are compressed and posted on Ethereum in batches.
[src:blockchain-scalability/data-availability] Batches represent thousands of individual offchain transactions in a single transaction on Ethereum.
[src:blockchain-scalability/data-availability] This reduces congestion on the base layer and reduces fees for users.
[src:blockchain-scalability/data-availability] However, it is only possible to trust the 'summary' transactions posted to Ethereum if the state change proposed can be independently verified and confirmed to be the result of applying all the individual offchain transactions.
[src:blockchain-scalability/data-availability] If rollup operators do not make the transaction data available for this verification, then they could send incorrect data to Ethereum.
[src:blockchain-scalability/data-availability] Optimistic rollups post compressed transaction data to Ethereum and wait for some amount of time (typically 7 days) to allow independent verifiers to check the data.
[src:blockchain-scalability/data-availability] If anyone identifies a problem, they can generate a fraud-proof and use it to challenge the rollup.
[src:blockchain-scalability/data-availability] This would cause the chain to roll back and omit the invalid block.
[src:blockchain-scalability/data-availability] This is only possible if data is available.
[src:blockchain-scalability/data-availability] Currently, there are two ways that optimistic rollups post transaction data to L1.
[src:blockchain-scalability/data-availability] Some rollups make data permanently available as `CALLDATA` which lives permanently onchain.
[src:blockchain-scalability/data-availability] With the implementation of EIP-4844, some rollups post their transaction data to cheaper blob storage instead.
[src:blockchain-scalability/data-availability] Independent verifiers have to query the blobs and raise their challenges within ~18 days before the data is deleted from Ethereum layer-1.
[src:blockchain-scalability/data-availability] Data availability is only guaranteed by the Ethereum protocol for that short fixed window.
[src:blockchain-scalability/data-availability] After that, it becomes the responsibility of other entities in the Ethereum ecosystem.
[src:blockchain-scalability/data-availability] Any node can verify data availability using DAS, i.e., by downloading small, random samples of the blob data.
[src:blockchain-scalability/data-availability] Zero-knowledge (ZK) rollups don't need to post transaction data since guarantee the correctness of state transitions.
[src:blockchain-scalability/data-availability] However, data availability is still an issue because we can't guarantee the functionality of the ZK-rollup (or interact with it) without access to its state data.
[src:blockchain-scalability/data-availability] For example, users cannot know their balances if an operator withholds details about the rollup’s state.
[src:blockchain-scalability/data-availability] Also, they cannot perform state updates using information contained in a newly added block.
[src:blockchain-scalability/data-availability] Data availability is different from data retrievability.
[src:blockchain-scalability/data-availability] Data availability is the assurance that full nodes have been able to access and verify the full set of transactions associated with a specific block.
[src:blockchain-scalability/data-availability] It does not necessarily follow that the data is accessible forever.
[src:blockchain-scalability/data-availability] Data retrievability is the ability of nodes to retrieve *historical information* from the blockchain.
[src:blockchain-scalability/data-availability] This historical data is not needed for verifying new blocks, it is only required for syncing full nodes from the genesis block or serving specific historical requests.
[src:blockchain-scalability/data-availability] The core Ethereum protocol is primarily concerned with data availability, not data retrievability.
[src:blockchain-scalability/data-availability] Data retrievability can be provided by a small population of archive nodes run by third parties, or it can be distributed across the network using decentralized file storage such as the Portal Network (opens in a new tab).
[src:blockchain-scalability/developers-scaling] As the number of people using Ethereum has grown, the blockchain has reached certain capacity limitations.
[src:blockchain-scalability/developers-scaling] This has driven up the cost of using the network, creating the need for "scaling solutions." There are multiple solutions being researched, tested and implemented that take different approaches to achieve similar goals.
[src:blockchain-scalability/developers-scaling] The main goal of scalability is to increase transaction speed (faster finality) and transaction throughput (higher number of transactions per second) without sacrificing decentralization or security.
[src:blockchain-scalability/developers-scaling] On the layer 1 Ethereum blockchain, high demand leads to slower transactions and nonviable gas prices.
[src:blockchain-scalability/developers-scaling] Increasing the network capacity in terms of speed and throughput is fundamental to the meaningful and mass adoption of Ethereum.
[src:blockchain-scalability/developers-scaling] While speed and throughput are important, it is essential that scaling solutions enabling these goals remain decentralized and secure.
[src:blockchain-scalability/developers-scaling] Keeping the barrier to entry low for node operators is critical in preventing a progression towards centralized and insecure computing power.
[src:blockchain-scalability/developers-scaling] Conceptually we first categorize scaling as either onchain scaling or offchain scaling.
[src:blockchain-scalability/developers-scaling] You should have a good understanding of all the foundational topics.
[src:blockchain-scalability/developers-scaling] Implementing scaling solutions is advanced as the technology is less battle-tested, and continues to be researched and developed.
[src:blockchain-scalability/developers-scaling] Onchain scaling requires changes to the Ethereum protocol (layer 1 ).
[src:blockchain-scalability/developers-scaling] For a long time, sharding the blockchain was expected to scale Ethereum.
[src:blockchain-scalability/developers-scaling] This was going to involve splitting the blockchain into discrete pieces (shards) to be verified by subsets of validators.
[src:blockchain-scalability/developers-scaling] However, scaling by layer-2 rollups has taken over as the primary scaling technique.
[src:blockchain-scalability/developers-scaling] This is supported by the addition of a new cheaper form of data attached to Ethereum blocks that is specially designed to make rollups cheap for users.
[src:blockchain-scalability/developers-scaling] Sharding is the process of splitting a database.
[src:blockchain-scalability/developers-scaling] Subsets of validators would be responsible for individual shards rather than keeping track of all of Ethereum.
[src:blockchain-scalability/developers-scaling] Sharding was on the Ethereum roadmap for a long time, and was once intended to be shipped before The Merge to proof-of-stake.
[src:blockchain-scalability/developers-scaling] However, the rapid development of layer 2 rollups and the invention of Danksharding (adding blobs of rollup data to Ethereum blocks that can be very efficiently verified by validators) has led the Ethereum community to favour rollup-centric scaling instead of scaling by sharding.
[src:blockchain-scalability/developers-scaling] This will also help to keep Ethereum's consensus logic simpler.
[src:blockchain-scalability/developers-scaling] Offchain solutions are implemented separately from layer 1 Mainnet - they require no changes to the existing Ethereum protocol.
[src:blockchain-scalability/developers-scaling] Some solutions, known as "layer 2" solutions, derive their security directly from layer 1 Ethereum consensus, such as optimistic rollups, zero-knowledge rollups or state channels.
[src:blockchain-scalability/developers-scaling] Other solutions involve the creation of new chains in various forms that derive their security separately from Mainnet, such as sidechains, validiums, or plasma chains.
[src:blockchain-scalability/developers-scaling] These solutions communicate with Mainnet but derive their security differently to obtain a variety of goals.
[src:blockchain-scalability/developers-scaling] This category of offchain solutions derives its security from Mainnet Ethereum.
[src:blockchain-scalability/developers-scaling] Layer 2 is a collective term for solutions designed to help scale your application by handling transactions off the Ethereum Mainnet (layer 1) while taking advantage of the robust decentralized security model of Mainnet.
[src:blockchain-scalability/developers-scaling] Transaction speed suffers when the network is busy, making the user experience poor for certain types of dapps.
[src:blockchain-scalability/developers-scaling] And as the network gets busier, gas prices increase as transaction senders aim to outbid each other.
[src:blockchain-scalability/developers-scaling] This can make using Ethereum very expensive.
[src:blockchain-scalability/developers-scaling] Most layer 2 solutions are centered around a server or cluster of servers, each of which may be referred to as a node, validator, operator, sequencer, block producer, or similar term.
[src:blockchain-scalability/developers-scaling] Depending on the implementation, these layer 2 nodes may be run by the individuals, businesses or entities that use them, or by a 3rd party operator, or by a large group of individuals (similar to Mainnet).
[src:blockchain-scalability/developers-scaling] Generally speaking, transactions are submitted to these layer 2 nodes instead of being submitted directly to layer 1 (Mainnet).
[src:blockchain-scalability/developers-scaling] For some solutions, the layer 2 instance then batches them into groups before anchoring them to layer 1, after which they are secured by layer 1 and cannot be altered.
[src:blockchain-scalability/developers-scaling] The details of how this is done vary significantly between different layer 2 technologies and implementations.
[src:blockchain-scalability/developers-scaling] A specific layer 2 instance may be open and shared by many applications, or may be deployed by one project and dedicated to supporting only their application.
[src:blockchain-scalability/developers-scaling] Rollups perform transaction execution outside layer 1 and then the data is posted to layer 1 where consensus is reached.
[src:blockchain-scalability/developers-scaling] As transaction data is included in layer 1 blocks, this allows rollups to be secured by native Ethereum security.
[src:blockchain-scalability/developers-scaling] State channels utilize multisig contracts to enable participants to transact quickly and freely offchain, then settle finality with Mainnet.
[src:blockchain-scalability/developers-scaling] This minimizes network congestion, fees, and delays.
[src:blockchain-scalability/developers-scaling] The two types of channels are currently state channels and payment channels.
[src:blockchain-scalability/developers-scaling] A sidechain is an independent EVM-compatible blockchain that runs in parallel to Mainnet.
[src:blockchain-scalability/developers-scaling] These are compatible with Ethereum via two-way bridges and run under their own chosen rules of consensus and block parameters.
[src:blockchain-scalability/developers-scaling] A plasma chain is a separate blockchain that is anchored to the main Ethereum chain and uses fraud proofs (like optimistic rollups) to arbitrate disputes.
[src:blockchain-scalability/developers-scaling] A Validium chain uses validity proofs like zero-knowledge rollups but data is not stored on the main layer 1 Ethereum chain.
[src:blockchain-scalability/developers-scaling] This can lead to 10k transactions per second per Validium chain and multiple chains can be run in parallel.
[src:blockchain-scalability/lightning-network] The **Lightning Network** (**LN**) is a payment protocol built on the bitcoin blockchain.
[src:blockchain-scalability/lightning-network] It is intended to enable fast transactions among participating nodes (independently run members of the network) and has been proposed as a solution to the bitcoin scalability problem.
[src:blockchain-scalability/lightning-network] Joseph Poon and Thaddeus Dryja published a Lightning Network white paper in February 2015.
[src:blockchain-scalability/lightning-network] Lightning Labs launched the Lightning Network in 2018 with the goal of reducing the cost and time required for cryptocurrency transactions.
[src:blockchain-scalability/lightning-network] Specifically, the bitcoin blockchain can only process around 7 transactions per second (compared to Visa Inc., which can process around 24,000 transactions per second).
[src:blockchain-scalability/lightning-network] Despite initial enthusiasm for the Lightning Network, reports on social media of failed transactions, security vulnerabilities, and over-complication led to a decline in interest.
[src:blockchain-scalability/lightning-network] The three major Lightning Network implementations are Lightning Network Daemon (LND) by Lightning Labs, Core Lightning (CLN) by Blockstream, and Eclair by ACINQ.
[src:blockchain-scalability/lightning-network] A fourth implementation library, Lightning Development Kit (LDK), is maintained by Spiral, a subsidiary of Block, Inc.
[src:blockchain-scalability/lightning-network] On January 19, 2019, pseudonymous Twitter user hodlonaut began a game-like promotional test of the Lightning Network by sending 100,000 satoshis (0.001 bitcoin) to a trusted recipient where each recipient added 10,000 satoshis ($0.34 at the time) to send to the next trusted recipient.
[src:blockchain-scalability/lightning-network] The "lightning torch" payment reached notable personalities including former Twitter A.K.A X CEO Jack Dorsey, Litecoin Creator Charlie Lee, Lightning Labs CEO Elizabeth Stark, and Binance CEO "CZ" Changpeng Zhao, among others.
[src:blockchain-scalability/lightning-network] Andreas Antonopoulos calls the Lightning Network a second layer routing network.
[src:blockchain-scalability/lightning-network] The payment channels allow participants to transfer money to each other without having to make all their transactions public on the blockchain.
[src:blockchain-scalability/lightning-network] This is secured by penalizing uncooperative participants.
[src:blockchain-scalability/lightning-network] When opening a channel, participants must commit an amount on the blockchain (a *funding transaction*).
[src:blockchain-scalability/lightning-network] Time-based script extensions like `CheckSequenceVerify` and `CheckLockTimeVerify` make the penalties possible.
[src:blockchain-scalability/lightning-network] Transacting parties use the Lightning Network by opening a payment channel and transferring (committing) funds to the relevant layer-1 blockchain (e.g. bitcoin) under a smart contract.
[src:blockchain-scalability/lightning-network] The parties then make any number of off-chain Lightning Network transactions that update the tentative distribution of the channel's funds, without broadcasting to the blockchain.
[src:blockchain-scalability/lightning-network] Whenever the parties have finished their transaction session, they close the payment channel, and the smart contract distributes the committed funds according to the transaction record.
[src:blockchain-scalability/lightning-network] The Lightning Network (LN) operates through bidirectional payment channels between two nodes, forming smart contracts that facilitate off-chain transactions.
[src:blockchain-scalability/lightning-network] If either party closes a channel, the final state is settled on the Bitcoin blockchain.
[src:blockchain-scalability/lightning-network] While this design enables faster and cheaper transactions, the necessity of on-chain transactions to open and close channels introduces scalability constraints.
[src:blockchain-scalability/lightning-network] To preserve privacy and security, the network employs an **onion routing** protocol, wherein each node in the path decrypts only enough information to determine the next hop, without knowledge of the payment's origin or final destination.
[src:blockchain-scalability/lightning-network] As of March 2026, the Lightning Network had over 17,000 public nodes and approximately 40,000 public payment channels, with a total network capacity of around 4,900 BTC.
[src:blockchain-scalability/lightning-network] Bitcoin was originally intended to be a peer-to-peer electronic cash system.
[src:blockchain-scalability/lightning-network] A notable early example occurred in May 2010 when Laszlo Hanyecz paid 10,000 BTC for two pizzas—an event now noted annually as *Bitcoin Pizza Day*.
[src:blockchain-scalability/lightning-network] As Bitcoin's value and network congestion increased, this use was no longer practical.
[src:blockchain-scalability/lightning-network] The Lightning Network is intended to address this and to make peer-to-peer payments more practical.
[src:blockchain-scalability/lightning-network] Several cryptocurrency wallets offer support for the Lightning Network, including Phoenix, Cash App, Muun, Zeus, and Breez.
[src:blockchain-scalability/segwit] SegWit had Bitcoin Improvement Proposal number BIP 141.
[src:blockchain-scalability/segwit] The declared purpose was to prevent nonintentional bitcoin transaction malleability; allow optional data transmission; and to bypass certain protocol restrictions (such as the block size limit) with a soft fork.
[src:blockchain-scalability/segwit] Segregated Witness was activated on 24 August 2017.
[src:blockchain-scalability/segwit] It was also intended to mitigate a blockchain size limitation problem that reduces Bitcoin transaction speed.
[src:blockchain-scalability/segwit] It does this by splitting the transaction into two segments, removing the unlocking signature ("witness" data) from the original portion and appending it as a separate structure at the end.
[src:blockchain-scalability/segwit] The original section would continue to hold the sender and receiver data, and the new "witness" structure would contain scripts and signatures.
[src:blockchain-scalability/segwit] The original data segment would be counted normally, but the "witness" segment would, in effect, be counted as a quarter of its real size.
[src:blockchain-scalability/segwit] Bitcoin is a cryptocurrency, a form of currency using cryptography to keep transactions secure.
[src:blockchain-scalability/segwit] A collection of bitcoin transactions prefaced by a block header, protected by proof of work, and recorded on a network of computers is called a "block".
[src:blockchain-scalability/segwit] All blocks are tied together sequentially by using a cryptographic hash on the previous block and storing its output in the next.
[src:blockchain-scalability/segwit] Each block contains information about who sends and receives a given unit of bitcoin (a transaction), as well as the signature(s) that approve each transaction.
[src:blockchain-scalability/segwit] Originally, there was no limit to the size of blocks.
[src:blockchain-scalability/segwit] However, this allowed malicious actors to make up fake "block" data that was very long as a form of denial-of-service attack (DoS attack).
[src:blockchain-scalability/segwit] These fake blocks would be detected, but doing so would take a very long time, slowing down the whole system.
[src:blockchain-scalability/segwit] Therefore, a block size limit of 1 MB was introduced.
[src:blockchain-scalability/segwit] The current Bitcoin blockchain design is regarded as having two shortcomings: scalability and malleability.
[src:blockchain-scalability/segwit] A new block is added to the chain at random intervals, averaging, by design, ten minutes (proof of work causes this delay).
[src:blockchain-scalability/segwit] Together with the limit on block-size, this limits the number of transactions that can be processed in a given time.
[src:blockchain-scalability/segwit] Some sites work around this problem by using "off-chain payments" conducting transactions without writing them to the blockchain which involves various trade-offs regarding trust and transaction finality.
[src:blockchain-scalability/segwit] Others have proposed changes to Bitcoin that would reform the block format in a backward-incompatible way.
[src:blockchain-scalability/segwit] For example, FlexTrans (Flexible Transactions) would make transactions smaller by changing how they are described to a "tag" system, allowing more transactions per block.
[src:blockchain-scalability/segwit] This is not compatible with systems that do not upgrade.
[src:blockchain-scalability/segwit] A transaction uses unused outputs from a previous transaction(s) known as unspent transaction outputs (UTXO).
[src:blockchain-scalability/segwit] This results in a chain of related transactions linked by their transaction identifier.
[src:blockchain-scalability/segwit] However, it is possible for someone to change (mutate) unconfirmed bitcoin transactions without making them invalid, which changes the transaction's identifier, making child transactions invalid (i.e., link between transactions are broken).
[src:blockchain-scalability/segwit] The signature data called the *witness* would be separated from the Merkle tree record of who is sending or receiving the bitcoins.
[src:blockchain-scalability/segwit] The witness data is moved to the end, and each byte of it would only count as one quarter of a "unit".
[src:blockchain-scalability/segwit] It also addresses signature malleability, by serializing signatures separately from the rest of the transaction data, so that the transaction ID is no longer malleable.
[src:blockchain-scalability/segwit] The activation window for the SegWit upgrade started at 00:00 UTC, 15 November 2016, and would run until 00:00 UTC, 15 November 2017.
[src:blockchain-scalability/segwit] SegWit would only be activated once at least 95% of miners signaled readiness for the upgrade across a target adjustment period of 2016 blocks.
[src:blockchain-scalability/segwit] On 9 August 2017, a milestone was reached when 100% of miners between blocks 477,792 to 479,807 signaled support for SegWit, which meant the SegWit upgrade was "locked in" and would be fully activated roughly two weeks later at the start of the following target adjustment period.
[src:blockchain-scalability/segwit] SegWit was then activated on 24 August 2017 at block height 481,824.
[src:blockchain-scalability/segwit] The bitcoin price rose almost 50% in the week following SegWit's activation.
[src:blockchain-scalability/segwit] Initially, most bitcoin transactions have not been able to use the upgrade.
[src:blockchain-scalability/segwit] In the first week of October, the proportion of network transactions using SegWit rose from 7% to 10%, indicating an increase in use rate.
[src:blockchain-scalability/segwit] A small group of mostly China-based bitcoin miners, that were unhappy with bitcoin's proposed SegWit improvement plans, pushed forward alternative plans for a split which created Bitcoin Cash.
[src:blockchain-scalability/segwit] As of February 2018, SegWit transactions exceed 30%.
[src:blockchain-scalability/segwit] Segregated Witness (BIP 141) should not be confused with SegWit2x (SegWit2Mb).
[src:blockchain-scalability/segwit] As of mid-2017, the SegWit2x proposal had support from over 90% of the hash rate.
[src:blockchain-scalability/segwit] However, the proposal has been controversial due to the limitation of project work to an invitation-only group of developers.
[src:blockchain-scalability/segwit] In mid-July 2017, it became evident that miners favored implementing the Segwit part of the agreement before 1 August 2017 UASF, aiming to mitigate the risk of a hard fork in the bitcoin network.
[src:blockchain-scalability/segwit] On 8 November 2017, the developers of SegWit2x announced that the hard fork planned for around 16 November 2017 was canceled due to a lack of consensus.
